Hypothesis¶

Research Question: What factors influence whether a booking is cancelled or not in the hospitality industry?

Background: Leveraging my undergraduate degree in International Hospitality Management and over six years of experience in the industry, I recognise that a multitude of factors can contribute to the cancellation of a booking. These factors can range from the price of the booking, the amount of deposit paid, the lead time prior to the stay, special requests, to the composition of the booking party (such as adult-only groups versus family bookings). I do also think that predictability will be low, given the nature of the data (hotels), cancellations happen for a number of reasons, all unique to the individual booking.

Importance of Historical Data: To understand the influence of these factors, it is crucial to collect and analyse the attributes of previously cancelled bookings. This data will allow us to identify patterns and correlations, which can inform predictive models to assess the likelihood of future cancellations.

Hypothesis: I hypothesise that the likelihood of a booking cancellation in the hospitality industry is influenced by various factors, including the booking price, the deposit amount, the lead time, special requests, and the type of booking party. Specifically, I predict that bookings with higher prices, smaller deposits, longer lead times, more special requests, and larger or family-oriented parties are more likely to be cancelled. Patterns in historical cancellation data will reveal these relationships.

Null and Alternative Hypotheses:

Null Hypothesis (H0): The price of the booking, the deposit paid, the lead time, the presence of special requests, and the type of booking party have no effect on the likelihood of booking cancellations in the hospitality industry.

Alternative Hypothesis (H1): The price of the booking, the deposit paid, the lead time, the presence of special requests, and the type of booking party significantly influence the likelihood of booking cancellations in the hospitality industry.

This formulation emphasises the importance of utilising historical data while addressing your research question and hypotheses. As always, these hypotheses will then be tested using data analysis techniques.

Checking for impossible data is a crucial step in data preprocessing. This procedure helps to identify and address outliers at an early stage, saving considerable time and effort down the line. Moreover, when implementing a machine learning model, ensuring the absence of impossible data is pivotal. Such anomalous data could lead to model misinterpretations, adversely impacting its performance and the accuracy of its predictions

Brief Explorative Data Summary¶

  • Pricing: The Average Daily Rate (ADR) is around 100 EUR per night, with fluctuations influenced by factors such as lead time, number of adults/ children in each booking and special requests to name a few things.
  • Guest Composition: Only 6.1% of bookings include children, indicating that the hotel primarily caters to adults.
  • Repeat Customers: Only 2.8% of guests are repeat customers, suggesting the hotel mainly attracts first-time guests. This highlights a potential area for improvement in guest retention strategies.
  • Special Requests: The majority of guests make one or two special requests, indicating that the hotel's standard services adequately cater to their needs.
  • Booking Changes: Around 14% of guests make changes to their bookings post-reservation. Understanding these modifications could provide insights into factors influencing the Average Daily Rate (ADR) and cancellation rates.
  • Cancellation Rates: Bookings made well in advance and higher-priced bookings have a slightly higher likelihood of being cancelled. Surprisingly, 'Non Refund' deposit type has the highest cancellation rate, suggesting factors beyond refundability influence cancellations.
  • Correlations: Weak to moderate correlations exist between variables such as adults and children, adults and ADR, children and ADR, adults and lead time, and children and lead time. The number of adults in a booking has a weak positive correlation with the number of special requests.
  • Data Distribution: Variables related to stays and lead time exhibit non-normal distributions, with positive skewness and kurtosis indicating some outliers and deviations in the data.

Overall, the analysis provides insights into the hotel's pricing strategies, guest demographics, repeat guest rate, special request patterns, booking changes, cancellation rates, and correlations among variables. The findings can guide improvements in guest retention, service customization, pricing optimization, and further investigation into the reasons behind booking modifications and cancellations.

R-squared (uncentered): The R-squared value measures the proportion of the variance in the dependent variable (ADR) that can be explained by the independent variables. Coefficients: The coefficients represent the standardized regression coefficients, which provide insights into the strength and direction of the relationship between each predictor and ADR. The coefficient for each predictor is accompanied by its standard error, t-value, and p-value.

x4 (LeadTime): The coefficient is -3.4627, indicating that a one-standard-deviation increase in the lead time is associated with a decrease in ADR.

x5 (TotalSpecialRequests): The coefficient is 4.3366, indicating that a one-standard-deviation increase in the total number of special requests is associated with a 4.3366-unit increase in ADR.

Omnibus and Prob(Omnibus): The Omnibus test evaluates the overall normality assumption of the residuals. In this case, the p-value is close to zero (0.000), indicating that the residuals do not follow a normal distribution.

Jarque-Bera (JB) and Prob(JB): The Jarque-Bera test further assesses the normality assumption of the residuals. The p-value is close to zero (0.000), suggesting that the residuals do not follow a normal distribution.

Durbin-Watson: The Durbin-Watson statistic measures the presence of autocorrelation in the residuals. A value close to 2 indicates no autocorrelation. In this case, the value is 0.233, suggesting the presence of positive autocorrelation.

AIC and BIC: These criteria provide information on the quality of the model fit. Lower values indicate a better fit. In this case, the AIC is 107,500, and the BIC is 107,600.

Notes: The notes provide additional information about the model, including the computation of R-squared (uncentered) and assumptions made regarding the model's structure.

Being a repeated guest (IsRepeatedGuest) has a negative effect, indicating that returning guests are less likely to cancel their bookings. Lead time (LeadTime) has a positive effect, implying that longer lead times between booking and the stay are associated with a higher probability of cancelation. The total number of special requests (TotalSpecialRequests) has a negative effect, suggesting that a higher number of special requests is associated with a lower likelihood of cancelation.

Based on the OLS Regression Results for predicting IsCancelled, the statistical results can be interpreted as follows:

R-squared (uncentered): The R-squared value measures the proportion of the variance in the dependent variable (IsCancelled) that can be explained by the independent variables. In this case, the uncentered R-squared value is 0.085, indicating that approximately 8.5% of the variance in IsCancelled is explained by the predictors in the model.

F-statistic and Prob (F-statistic): The F-statistic tests the overall significance of the regression model. In this case, the F-statistic is 163.8, and the corresponding p-value is very close to zero (5.19e-167). This suggests that the model, as a whole, is statistically significant.

Coefficients: The coefficients represent the standardized regression coefficients, which provide insights into the strength and direction of the relationship between each predictor and IsCancelled. The coefficient for each predictor is accompanied by its standard error, t-value, and p-value.

x1: The coefficient is 0.0257, indicating that a one-standard-deviation increase in the predictor x1 is associated with a 0.0257 increase in the odds of cancellation (IsCancelled).

x2: The coefficient is 0.0086, suggesting that a one-standard-deviation increase in the predictor x2 is associated with a smaller increase in the odds of cancellation. However, the p-value (0.167) indicates that this relationship is not statistically significant at a conventional significance level (e.g., α = 0.05).

x3: The coefficient is -0.0190, suggesting that a one-standard-deviation increase in the predictor x3 is associated with a decrease in the odds of cancellation. The p-value (0.003) indicates that this relationship is statistically significant.

x4: The coefficient is 0.1296, indicating that a one-standard-deviation increase in the predictor x4 is associated with a larger increase in the odds of cancellation. The p-value is very close to zero (0.000), indicating a statistically significant relationship.

x5: The coefficient is -0.1008, suggesting that a one-standard-deviation increase in the predictor x5 is associated with a decrease in the odds of cancellation. The p-value is very close to zero (0.000), indicating a statistically significant relationship.

Omnibus and Prob(Omnibus): The Omnibus test evaluates the overall normality assumption of the residuals. In this case, the p-value is very close to zero (0.000), indicating that the residuals do not follow a normal distribution.

Jarque-Bera (JB) and Prob(JB): The Jarque-Bera test further assesses the normality assumption of the residuals. The p-value is very close to zero (0.000), suggesting that the residuals do not follow a normal distribution.

Durbin-Watson: The Durbin-Watson statistic measures the presence of autocorrelation in the residuals. A value close to 2 indicates no autocorrelation. In this case, the value is 1.204, suggesting a slight positive autocorrelation.

AIC and BIC: These criteria provide information on the quality of the model fit. Lower values indicate a better fit. In this case, the AIC is 15,280, and the BIC is 15,310.

Notes: The notes provide additional information about the model, including the computation of R-squared (uncentered) and assumptions made regarding the model's structure.

Overall, the model provides a modest fit to the data, as evidenced by the low R-squared value. The predictors collectively explain approximately 8.5% of the variance in IsCancelled. The statistically significant coefficients indicate that some predictors have a significant relationship with the likelihood of cancellation. However, the non-significant p-value for x2 suggests that it may not have a meaningful impact on the cancellation outcome. The presence of non-normality in the residuals and positive autocorrelation should be considered when interpreting the results.

Conclusion¶

The analysis conducted is aimed at understanding the factors that influence booking cancellations and to predict whether a booking will be cancelled or not. The analysis involved working with a large dataset collected from the hotel chain's Property Management System database. The results of the analysis are as follows:

For the IsCancelled Model:

Training set R squared: 0.226 Test set R squared: 0.234

These R squared values indicate that the model explains approximately 22.6% of the variance in booking cancellations in the training set and 23.4% in the test set. This suggests that the model provides some level of prediction for whether a booking will be cancelled or not, but there is still a significant amount of unexplained variation.

For the ADR Model:

Training set R squared: 0.277 Test set R squared: 0.236

The R squared values for the ADR model indicate that approximately 27.7% of the variance in the Average Daily Rate (ADR) is explained by the model in the training set, while 23.6% is explained in the test set. This suggests that the model provides some level of prediction for ADR, but again, there is a substantial amount of unexplained variation. While the ADR model performs slightly better in terms of explaining the variance, both models have limitations and provide only modest predictive power for their respective target variables

The data analysis aimed to understand the characteristics of cancelled and uncancelled bookings and identify the factors that influence booking cancellations. Considering the inherent difficulty of predicting hotel booking cancellations, achieving a predictive accuracy of approximately 20-27% is an accomplishment. The ability to achieve such levels of accuracy in a domain characterized by a considerable degree of randomness highlights the effectiveness of the models and the value they provide in assisting decision-making processes.

Amazing Hotels should adopt the KNN regression model based off of the ADR as it gives a slightly higher prediction percentage. The Logistic Regression model did achieve the result of 1.0 but this accuracy could be the fault of overfitting, this runs the risk of over-optimistic Performance results, which in this case would be likely as the KNN regression model at best could predict at 27% accuracy and we have established this is a difficult topic in terms of predictability.

In summary, while the analysis offers valuable insights into the factors influencing hotel booking cancellations, it is important to acknowledge the intrinsic challenges associated with predicting such outcomes. The highly personalised nature of cancellations, influenced by a multitude of individual-specific factors, limits the attainable predictive accuracy. Nevertheless, the achieved predictive accuracy of 20-27% represents a commendable achievement given the inherent unpredictability associated with hotel booking cancellations.
